                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                      CM calls for big business
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                              
	Bhubaneswar, Dec. 11: Chief minister Naveen Patnaik today called upon large industries to come forward and play a catalytic role in the promotion of downstream and ancillary units.        
	Its imperative for large industries to do a detailed analysis and suggest the kind of products that can be produced by downstream ones, said the chief minister while inaugurating a seminar on development of downstream industries by way of value addition here today.        
	They should also provide suitable infrastructure support for setting up of new metal-based industries, he said.        
	In fact, the states Industrial Policy Resolution, 2007, recognises ancillary and downstream industries as a thrust sector and provides maximum incentives to such incentives, Naveen said.         
	The Micro, Small and Medium Enterprises Development Policy, 2009, also provided additional incentives to small-scale industries, he added.                                
	Claiming that Orissa has been successful in attracting a large number of investors in diverse sectors such as mining, steel, aluminium, power, cement, petroleum, petro-chemicals and information technology, Naveen quoted the report of the Centre for Monitoring Indian Economy, which placed Orissa among the top two states in India in terms of value of total projects under implementation.        
	Besides, according to a World Bank study, Bhubaneswar is the third favoured place among 19 other cities in the country in terms of doing business in India, he said.        
	According to official figures, more than 80 private companies have signed MoUs with the state government to set up 49 steel plants, 21 thermal plants and several other industries.                                                                                                                                                           
